If you sell products online, you've probably had this thought: "Should I keep paying Etsy, or should I build my own website?" It's a fair question, and the honest answer is that it depends on where you are in your business. Let's break it down.

## What Etsy actually costs

Etsy's fees look small individually, but they stack up fast:

- **Listing fee**: $0.20 per item (renewed every 4 months or when sold)
- **Transaction fee**: 6.5% of the sale price (including shipping)
- **Payment processing**: 3% + $0.25 per transaction
- **Offsite ads fee**: 15% on sales from Etsy's advertising (12% if you sell over $10K/year) — and you can't opt out once you hit $10K in annual sales
- **Currency conversion**: 2.5% if applicable

On a $50 product, here's the math:

| Fee | Amount |
|---|---|
| Listing | $0.20 |
| Transaction (6.5%) | $3.25 |
| Payment processing | $1.75 |
| **Total (no ads)** | **$5.20 (10.4%)** |
| Offsite ads (if triggered) | $7.50 |
| **Total (with ads)** | **$12.70 (25.4%)** |

That's a quarter of your revenue on a single sale when offsite ads kick in. And you have no control over when Etsy decides to advertise your product.

For a seller doing $3,000/month on Etsy, fees run $300-$750/month depending on how many sales come through offsite ads. That's $3,600-$9,000 per year in platform fees.

## What Etsy gives you in return

Here's where we have to be honest, because this is where a lot of "leave Etsy" articles get it wrong: **Etsy gives you free traffic.** Not free as in no cost — you're paying those fees — but free as in you don't have to figure out how to get people to your website. Etsy has 90+ million active buyers who are already searching for products. If your SEO within Etsy is decent, customers find you without you running a single ad.

That's genuinely valuable, especially when you're starting out. Building your own store means you also have to build your own audience. That takes time, effort, and usually some ad spend.

Other things Etsy provides:
- **Built-in trust**: Buyers trust Etsy's checkout, reviews, and buyer protection
- **Search visibility**: Your products show up in Etsy search and Google Shopping
- **Infrastructure**: You don't think about hosting, SSL certificates, or payment processing
- **Mobile app**: Etsy's app puts your products in front of people browsing on their phones

## When to stay on Etsy

Etsy is probably the right choice if:

- **You're testing a product idea.** You have 10-20 products and you're figuring out what sells. The fees are worth the exposure while you learn.
- **This is a side hustle.** You sell a few items a month and don't want to manage a website. Etsy handles everything.
- **You don't have repeat customers yet.** If every sale is a new customer discovering you through Etsy search, that platform traffic is doing real work for you.
- **You sell under $1,000/month.** At this volume, the fees are manageable and the cost of a custom store is harder to justify.

There's no shame in any of these. Etsy is a legitimate sales channel, and plenty of successful businesses use it as one part of their strategy forever.

## When to build your own store

The math starts to shift when:

- **You have repeat customers.** If people come back to buy from you specifically — not because they found you on Etsy — you're paying Etsy 10-25% for customers they didn't bring you. That's the most expensive mistake on the platform.
- **You sell over $2,000/month consistently.** At $2K/month, you're paying $2,400-$6,000/year in Etsy fees. A custom online store costs $3,500-$7,500 once, plus Stripe's flat 2.9% + $0.30 per transaction. The store pays for itself in year one.
- **You want to build a brand.** On Etsy, you're a shop inside a mall. Customers remember Etsy, not you. On your own site, every visit reinforces your brand, your story, your packaging. That's how side hustles become real businesses.
- **You want your customer data.** On Etsy, you get a shipping address. On your own store, you get email addresses, purchase history, and the ability to market directly to people who already like your products. An email list of 500 past customers is worth more than 5,000 Etsy followers.
- **You're tired of algorithm changes.** Etsy regularly changes how search works, and sellers wake up to find their traffic cut in half overnight. Your own store's traffic sources — Google, social media, email — are diversified.

## The hybrid approach

The smartest sellers we work with don't choose one or the other. They do both:

1. **Keep your Etsy shop** for discovery and new customer acquisition
2. **Build your own store** as your primary home base
3. **Move repeat customers to your site** with incentives (10% off first direct order, free shipping, loyalty program)
4. **Use Etsy as a funnel**, not a foundation

Over time, the ratio shifts. Etsy goes from 90% of your sales to 50% to 30%, as your direct audience grows. But you're never fully dependent on a platform you don't control.

## What a custom store actually involves

When we build an online store — like the setup we did for Peach and Thread Boutique — here's what's included:

- **Product pages** with photos, descriptions, variants (size, color), and inventory tracking
- **Shopping cart and checkout** powered by Stripe (2.9% + $0.30 per transaction — about a third of Etsy's total fees)
- **Your own domain** (yourbrand.com, not etsy.com/shop/yourbrand)
- **Mobile-optimized design** that matches your brand identity
- **Email collection** built into the shopping experience
- **SEO setup** so your products show up in Google search
- **Hosting on Cloudflare's CDN** — fast globally, no monthly hosting bill

Our Store tier runs $3,500-$7,500 depending on how many products, features, and integrations you need. There's no monthly platform fee. Stripe charges per transaction, and that's it.

## The break-even math

Let's compare a seller doing $3,000/month:

| | Etsy | Own Store |
|---|---|---|
| Monthly fees | $300-$750 | ~$100 (Stripe only) |
| Annual fees | $3,600-$9,000 | ~$1,200 |
| Year 1 cost (with build) | $3,600-$9,000 | $4,700-$8,700 |
| Year 2 cost | $3,600-$9,000 | ~$1,200 |
| Year 3 cost | $3,600-$9,000 | ~$1,200 |

By year 2, the own-store path is saving $2,400-$7,800 per year. And that gap only widens as your sales grow, because Stripe's percentage stays flat while Etsy's fees compound with features like offsite ads.

## The honest bottom line

Etsy is a great place to start selling. It's a terrible place to build a business long-term if you're leaving 20-25% of your revenue on the table for customers who already know your name.

If you're doing consistent sales and you have customers who come back, it's time to give them a better place to shop — one that's yours.

